|Roberto Arrelucea]] (2007\u2013May 8)\n*{{flagicon|Peru}} [[V\u00edctor Rivera (football manager)|V\u00edctor Rivera]] (Dec 15, 2010\u2013??)\n*{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Mario Viera]] (July 2011\u20131?)\n*{{flagicon|Peru}} [[Franco Navarro]] (Dec 6, 2013\u201314)\n*{{flagicon|Argentina}} [[\u00c1ngel Comizzo]] (2016)\n*{{flagicon|Colombia}} Francisco Cort\u00e9s (2017)\n*{{flagicon|Peru}} [[Jos\u00e9 del Solar]] (2018-)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of football clubs in Peru]]\n*[[Peruvian football league system]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110806181307/http://www.clubdeportivoucv.edu.pe/ Official website]\n*{{Facebook|215296224645}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{YouTube|user=clubucv}}\n\n{{Primera Divisi\u00f3n Peruana}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Universidad Cesar Vallejo}}\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Trujillo, Peru]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Peru]]\n[[Category:University and college association football clubs]]\n", "name_user": "Ericbaudouin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Club_Deportivo_Universidad_C%C3%A9sar_Vallejo"}
{"title_page": "The Most Beautiful Girl in the World (Prince song)", "text_new": "{{Cleanup|date=May 2019|reason=The recently added paragraph on the plagiarism needs a rewrite}}{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\n| cover      = PrinceTheMostBeautifulGirlInTheWorld.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]\n| album      = [[The Beautiful Experience]] ''and'' [[The Gold Experience]]\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Beautiful\"|\"Beautiful\" (Extended Club Mix by [[Simon Harris (musician)|Simon Harris]]) <small>(UK 12\")</small>|\"Beautiful Beats\" <small>(UK 12\")</small>}}\n| released   = February 24, 1994\n| format     = 7\" single<br>[[12-inch single|12\" single]]<br>[[Cassette single]]<br>[[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 1993\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Soft rock]]|[[contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[pop music|pop]]}}\n| length     = 4:07 (single edit)<br>4:37 (original mix)<br>4:25 (''Gold Experience'' version)\n| label      = [[NPG Records|NPG]], [[Bellmark Records|Bellmark]], [[Edel AG|Edel]]\n| writer     = Prince\n| producer   = Prince, Ricky Peterson\n| prev_title = [[Peach (Prince song)|Peach]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[Pope (Prince song)|Pope]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{Youtube|-mATCxIqOjg|\u00abThe Most Beautiful Girl in The World\u00bb}}}}\n  {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Prince (UK)\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Controversy (song)|Controversy]]\n | prev_year  = 1993\n | title      = The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\n | year       = 1994\n | next_title = [[Letitgo (song)|Letitgo]]\n | next_year  = 1994\n}}\n}}{{List|Liza Hopkins=My love|date=November 2016}}\n\n'''The Most Beautiful Girl in the World is Kristina Kuchel. She is drop dead gorgeous very smart and overall amazing.'''\n\nShe also has a body that looks like Kylie Jenner. #stormiismyonlyworld \n\n\n\n<br />\n\n==Development==\nThe original track is a slow-grooving [[ballad]] that serenades a beautiful woman, his soon-to-be fianc\u00e9, [[Mayte Garcia]]. The song was played during the [[Miss USA]] pageant in 1994, but not in full. It was widely advertised in news and trade magazines that a new song from Prince would be premiered at the pageant. The ads had Prince sitting in a chair with a hat pulled down over his face, and Garcia standing next to his chair. The song was officially released on February 24, 1994. It later appeared on ''[[The Gold Experience]]''.\n\nThe version on ''The Gold Experience'' is remixed. The drums are more crisp in the mix, and there are slight instrumental changes. There are also added sound effects and instrumental breaks in the second version. The bridge is slightly more robust as well. The song is still based in light [[guitar]], [[Electronic keyboard|keyboards]] and live [[Drum kit|drums]]. Although most of the song is sung in falsetto with Prince reaching some extremely high notes, the final bridge has him using his regular voice as well as a lower baritone range in one small segment.\n\nThe song was a worldwide hit and established Prince's ability to succeed commercially under his new name, peaking at No. 3 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It was certified [[RIAA certification|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] and sold 700,000 copies domestically.<ref>{{cite certification|region=United States|artist=Prince|title=The Most Beautiful Girl in the World}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uAsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA57|title=Best-Selling Records of 1994|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=BPI Communications|date=January 21, 1995|page=57|issn=0006-2510|volume=107|number=3}}</ref> However, the song was his last top 10 hit on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 during his lifetime.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Trust |first1=Gary |title=Desiigner Holds Off Drake Atop Hot 100, Prince & Beyonce Hit Top 10 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7350427/desiigner-drake-hot-100-prince-beyonce-top-10 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.com]] |accessdate=2017-12-09 |date=2016-05-02}}</ref> \n\nIt became his first and only United Kingdom No. 1 single under any name as a performer.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=David|title=[[British Hit Singles & Albums]]|publisher=Guinness World Records Limited|year=2006|isbn=1-904994-10-5|edition=19th|location=London|page=565}}</ref> He did have two other United Kingdom number ones as a songwriter: the 1984 hit single \"[[I Feel for You]]\" covered by [[Chaka Khan]] and [[Sin\u00e9ad O'Connor]]'s 1990 cover of \"[[Nothing Compares 2 U]]\". Prince danced to his own song \"The Most Beautiful Girl In The World\" after the World Music Awards at an after show event with Kylie Minogue in 1994.\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[AllMusic]] editor Daniel Browne called it a \"dreamy slice of soul-pop in the style of [[The Delfonics|Delfonics]] mastermind [[Thom Bell]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-beautiful-experience-ep-mw0000115622|title=Prince - The Beautiful Experience EP|work=AllMusic|date=|accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> Editor [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] wrote in his review of ''[[The Gold Experience]]'', that it has a \"more immediate\" melody and described it as a \"the Philly soul tribute\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/gold-experience-mw0000121276|title=Prince - Gold Experience|work=AllMusic|date=|accessdate=2020-02-18}}</ref> ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'' wrote about the song, \"Never one to sit idly by. Prince returns after a short sabbatical with this new funky single, released through a new deal with A1 Bell's Bellmark Records (...) Already making waves at Urban and top-40 radio, this keyboard-heavy, lushly produced track breaks no new ground for Prince, but looks like a sure bet for chart success. Expect to hear this song of female worship at the junior prom come June.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/90s/1994/CB-1994-03-12.pdf|title=Pop Singles: Reviews|publisher=Cashbox magazine|page=11|accessdate=2020-01-21}}</ref> Tom Ewing from [[Freaky Trigger]] described the song as a \"high, heady, perfume-drunk ballad drawing from the well of Thom Bell's work with the Delfonics and [[The Stylistics|Stylistics]].\" He added, \"Prince disciplines himself, staying almost throughout at the absolute top of his register, a high-wire act he pulls off without a hitch but also without any moment which completely sells the decision. The music is opulent boudoir funk, the best line \u2013 \"How can I get through days when I can't get through hours?\" \u2013 is very good, and there's a casual classiness to the record.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freakytrigger.co.uk/popular/2013/01/the-artist-formerly-known-as-prince-the-most-beautiful-girl-in-the-world/#more-23809|title=THE ARTIST FORMERLY KNOWN AS PRINCE \u2013 \u201cThe Most Beautiful Girl In The World\u201d|publisher=[[Freaky Trigger]]|date=2013-01-02|accessdate=2020-03-06}}</ref> Lars Nielsen from ''[[Gaffa (magazine)|Gaffa]]'' called it a \"pop-pearl\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://gaffa.e-pages.pub/titles/gaffa/9520/publications/136/pages/22|title=Prince: Come|magazine=[[Gaffa (magazine)|Gaffa]]|date=1994-09-01|page=23|accessdate=2020-03-29|language=Danish}}</ref> Alexis Petridis from [[The Guardian]] said \"it's a deft homage to the super-soft 70s soul of the Delfonics and the Stylistics\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/sep/12/prince-50-greatest-singles-ranked|title=Prince's 50 greatest singles \u2013 ranked!|magazine=[[The Guardian]]|date=2019-09-12|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref> Mark Carlson from ''[[The Michigan Daily]]'' picked it as one of the \"highlights\" from the album and described the song as \"super-sappy (yet somehow wonderful)\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=CBBKAAAAIBAJ|title=RECORDS: The Artist Formerly Known as Prince - The Gold Experience|magazine=[[The Michigan Daily]]|date=1995-10-02|accessdate=2020-03-15}}</ref> John Kilgo from ''The Network Forty'' said that the single \"may be Prince's strongest since \"[[Cream (Prince song)|Cream]]\"\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Network-40/94/Network-40-1994-03-11.pdf|title=Mainstream: Music Meeting|magazine=The Network Forty|date=1994-03-11|page=24|accessdate=2020-03-29}}</ref> In 2012, ''Porcys'' listed the song at number 5 in their ranking of \"100 Singles 1990-1999\".<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Singli 1990-1999|url=http://www.porcys.com/ranking/100-singli-1990-1999/10/|website=Porcys|date=2012-08-20|language=Polish|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref> Tim Marsh from ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]'' noted that it \"displayed a confident touch\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://selectmagazinescans.monkeon.co.uk/showpage.php?file=wp-content/uploads/2014/06/albums43.jpg|title=Reviews: New Albums|magazine=[[Select (magazine)|Select]]|date=1994-09-01|page=100|accessdate=2020-03-03}}</ref>     \n\n== Personnel<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.princevault.com/index.php?title=The_Most_Beautiful_Girl_In_The_World|title=The Most Beautiful Girl In The World - Prince Vault|website=www.princevault.com|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref> ==\n\n* [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] - all vocals and instruments, except where noted\n* [https://www.rickypeterson.com/ Ricky Peterson] - additional keyboards (as \"Ricky P.\")\n* James \"Jimi\" Behringer - additional guitar\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\" was directed by Prince and American film director and producer [[Antoine Fuqua]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://imvdb.com/video/prince/the-most-beautiful-girl-in-the-world|title=The Most Beautiful Girl in the World (1994) by Prince|publisher=IMVDb.com|accessdate=2018-10-18}}</ref>\t\n\n==Track listings==\n;Single\n# \"The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\" (single edit) \u2013 4:06\n# \"Beautiful\" (single edit) \u2013 3:54\n\n;United Kingdom 12\"\n# \"The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\" \u2013 4:07\n# \"Beautiful\" \u2013 3:57\n# \"Beautiful\" (extended club mix by [[Simon Harris (musician)|Simon Harris]]) \u2013 6:25\n# \"Beautiful Beats\" - 3:30\n\n== [[Plagiarism]] case ==\n[[Bruno Bergonzi]] co-wrote with [[Michele Vicino]] the song \"Takin' Me to Paradise\", published on 1983 by [[Warner Chappell Italy]]. The session vocalist was Raynard. J, the pseudonym of Jay Rolandi. The song appeared on a number of compilations, which was internationally distributed. An Italian court ruled on 2003 that [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]'s 1994 hit, \"The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\", was a plagiarism from the song by the two Italian writers. Bergonzi and Vicino won on appeal in 2007. The third and final sentence, by the [[Supreme Court of Cassation (Italy)|Court of Cassation]] of Rome, arrived in May 2015. Italian collecting society SIAE recognizes Bergonzi and Vicino as the authors of \"The Most Most Beautiful Girl in the World\" music.<ref>Mark Worden, ''Prince's Italian Plagiarism Case Drags On'', [https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7445762/princes-italian-plagiarism-case], Retrieved 10 February 2019. Roger Nelson Prince, Controversy Music inc., Michele Vicino, Bruno Bergonzi, [https://www.dirittodautore.it/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/SentCassCiv11225_2015.pdf]. Retrieved 16 April 2019.</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1994\u20131995)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|1|artist=The Symbol|song=The Most Beautiful Girl in the World|rowheader=true|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|5|artist=The Symbol|song=The Most Beautiful Girl in the World|rowheader=true|accessdate=October 12, 201