{"title_page": "Some Are Lakes", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Some Are Lakes\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Land of Talk]]\n| cover      = File:LandofTalk_Lakes.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 7, 2008\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Indie rock]]\n| length     = 49:40\n| label      = [[Secret City Records]] (Canada)<br>[[Saddle Creek Records]] (US)\n| producer   = [[Justin Vernon]] and [[Land of Talk]]\n| prev_title = [[Applause Cheer Boo Hiss]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[Cloak and Cipher]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n\n'''''Some Are Lakes''''' is the first full-length album by [[Canada|Canadian]] indie rock band [[Land of Talk]], released October 7, 2008, on [[Secret City Records]] in Canada and [[Saddle Creek Records]] in the [[United States]].\n\nThe album was produced by [[Justin Vernon]] of the American indie folk group [[Bon Iver]].<ref>[http://stereogum.com/17491/new_land_of_talk_some_are_lakes/mp3s/ \"New Land of Talk: Some Are Lakes\"]. [[Stereogum]], August 27, 2008.</ref>\n{{Album reviews\n|MC=(74/100)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/some-are-lakes/land-of-talk | title=Land of Talk | work=Metacritic | accessdate=30 October 2016}}</ref>\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score={{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/some-are-lakes-mw0000798664 | title=Some Are Lakes Review | work=AllMusic | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Phares, Heather}}</ref>\n|rev2=[[BBC Music]]\n|rev2score=(mixed)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/bv25/ | title=Some Are Lakes Review | work=BBC Music | date=2008 | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Gill, Jaime}}</ref>\n|rev3=[[PopMatters]]\n|rev3score={{rating|7|10}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/65998-land-of-talk-some-are-lakes/ | title=Some Are Lakes | work=PopMatters | date=3 December 2008 | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Berry, David}}</ref>\n|rev4=[[New York Times]]\n|rev4score=(favorable)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/19/arts/music/19play.html | title=Travelers Through Time and Space | work=New York Times | date=19 October 2008 | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Chinen, Nate}}</ref>\n|rev5=[[Pitchfork Media]]\n|rev5score=(6.9/10)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12235-some-are-lakes/ | title=Some Are Lakes | work=Pitchfork Media | date=1 October 2008 | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Bevan, David}}</ref>\n|rev6=[[Robert Christgau]]\n|rev6score={{rating-Christgau|hm1}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cg2009-05.php | title=Consumer Guide | work=MSN Music | date=May 2009 | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Christgau, Robert}}</ref>\n|rev7=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]\n|rev7score={{rating|3|5|full=TMT full.svg|half=TMT half.svg|empty=TMT empty.svg|rating=mark}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/land-talk-some-are-lakes | title=Some Are Lakes Review | work=Tiny Mix Tapes | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Bearmcnair}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Tracklist\n| title1 = Yuppy Flu\n| length1 = 5:08\n| title2 = Death by Fire\n| length2 = 4:10\n| title3 = The Man Who Breaks Things (Dark Shuffle)\n| length3 = 2:11\n| title4 = Some Are Lakes\n| length4 = 3:41\n| title5 = Give Me Back My Heart Attack\n| length5 = 4:27\n| title6 = It's Okay\n| length6 = 4:54\n| title7 = Young Bridge\n| length7 = 3:45\n| title8 = Corner Phone\n| length8 = 3:14\n| title9 = Got a Call\n| length9 = 4:19\n| title10 = Troubled\n| length10 = 3:23\n}}\n\n\n==Critical reception==\nIn October of 2008, David Bevan of [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] gave the album a 6.9/10. With oral influence from bands Sonic Youth, Fleetwood Mac, and  Afghan Whigs, Bevan reports that \"...while just as thorny and gnarled in parts...its calms are ultimately more haunting and compelling than its many storms.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/12235-some-are-lakes/ | title=Some Are Lakes | work=Pitchfork Media | date=1 October 2008 | accessdate=17 April 2020 | author=Bevan, David}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Some Are Lakes}}\n[[Category:2008 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Land of Talk albums]]\n[[Category:Saddle Creek Records albums]]\n[[Category:Secret City Records albums]]\n\n{{2000s-indie-rock-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Some Are Lakes\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Land of Talk]]\n| cover      = File:LandofTalk_Lakes.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 7, 2008\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Indie rock]]\n| length     = 49:40\n| label      = [[Secret City Records]] (Canada)<br>[[Saddle Creek Records]] (US)\n| producer   = [[Justin Vernon]] and [[Land of Talk]]\n| prev_title = [[Applause Cheer Boo Hiss]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[Cloak and Cipher]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n\n'''''Some Are Lakes''''' is the first full-length album by [[Canada|Canadian]] indie rock band [[Land of Talk]], released October 7, 2008, on [[Secret City Records]] in Canada and [[Saddle Creek Records]] in the [[United States]].\n\nThe album was produced by [[Justin Vernon]] of the American indie folk group [[Bon Iver]].<ref>[http://stereogum.com/17491/new_land_of_talk_some_are_lakes/mp3s/ \"New Land of Talk: Some Are Lakes\"]. [[Stereogum]], August 27, 2008.</ref>\n{{Album reviews\n|MC=(74/100)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/some-are-lakes/land-of-talk | title=Land of Talk | work=Metacritic | accessdate=30 October 2016}}</ref>\n|rev1=[[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score={{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/some-are-lakes-mw0000798664 | title=Some Are Lakes Review | work=AllMusic | accessdate=30 October 2016 | author=Phares, Heather}}</ref>\n|rev2=[[BBC Music]]\n|rev2score=(mixed)<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/bv25/ | title=Some Are Lakes Re